---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="The temple: history, sthala purana and architecture | Chennakesava Swamy, Markapur"
  description="The legend of Kesi and Adisesha, the milkmaid Marika who gave Markapur its name, the 135-foot Galigopuram, eighteen Vijayanagara inscriptions, and six musical pillars."
>
  <h1>The temple</h1>
  <p class="page-te">శ్రీ లక్ష్మీ చెన్నకేశవ స్వామి దేవస్థానం</p>

  <h2>Why Vishnu stayed here</h2>
  <p>
    The demon <strong>Kesi</strong> harassed the ascetics who meditated along the
    <strong>Gundlakamma</strong>. The rishi <strong>Markandeya</strong> sought Vishnu's
    protection. Kesi could be slain only by a serpent, so Vishnu sent
    <strong>Adisesha</strong>, who killed him. Markandeya then asked Vishnu to remain in
    that place, and he stayed as Chennakesava with Mahalakshmi beside him.
  </p>
  <p>
    <em>Chennakesava</em> means the beautifully adorned. Vishnu is
    <em>Alankara Priya</em>, fond of ornament, and it is by that name he is worshipped here.
  </p>

  <h2>How the town got its name</h2>
  <p>
    A milkmaid named <strong>Marika</strong> is said to have worshipped Vishnu with milk.
    Blessed with a son, she built a temple in gratitude. The settlement that grew around
    it became <em>Marikapuram</em>, and in time <strong>Markapur</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The town sat in Kurnool district until 1971, when it passed to Prakasam. It has
    manufactured slate for generations, the grey-green stone this site takes its colour from.
  </p>

  <svg class="kolam-rule" aria-hidden="true"><rect width="100%" height="100%" fill="url(#kolam)" /></svg>

  <h2>The Galigopuram</h2>
  <p>
    The tower stands <strong>135 feet</strong> and was not raised at once. Seven tiers
    recede above a tall plain gateway, each face carrying rows of niches, and the
    barrel-vaulted shikhara at the summit flares wider than the tier beneath it, carrying
    five kalasas along its ridge.
  </p>

  <!-- The drawing is the argument: four centuries of building, and the joins are visible.
       Decorative to assistive tech, because the same dates follow as real text below. -->
  <figure class="tower">
    <!-- Two drawings, not one with a hidden group: the wide viewBox exists only to hold
         the annotations, so reusing it on a phone strands the tower in the left third. -->
    <svg class="tower-plain" viewBox="0 0 200 470" aria-hidden="true">
      <use href="#gopuram" />
    </svg>
    <svg class="tower-anno" viewBox="0 0 470 500" aria-hidden="true">
      <g style="color:var(--ink)"><use href="#gopuram" transform="translate(60,0) scale(0.92)" /></g>
      <g>
        <g stroke="var(--gold-line)" stroke-width="1" fill="none">
          <path d="M196,100 H300" /><path d="M216,317 H300" /><path d="M214,380 H300" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--kumkum)" font-family="ui-monospace,Menlo,monospace" font-size="12" font-weight="600">
          <text x="304" y="104">1837</text>
          <text x="304" y="321">1405–59</text>
          <text x="304" y="384">1425</text>
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink-soft)" font-family="system-ui" font-size="10.5">
          <text x="304" y="118">upper storeys added</text>
          <text x="304" y="335">first storey, Vijayanagara</text>
          <text x="304" y="398">walls, 18 inscriptions</text>
        </g>
      </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption class="tower-key">
      <ul>
        <li><b>1405–59</b> First storey, Vijayanagara, in the reign of Krishnadeva Raya</li>
        <li><b>1425</b> Walls raised, carrying eighteen inscriptions</li>
        <li><b>1837</b> Upper storeys added, bringing it to 135 feet</li>
      </ul>
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h3>Inside the complex</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Eighteen inscriptions</strong><br />
            <span style="color:var(--ink-soft); font-size:15px">Cut into the temple walls, recording the life and culture of the period</span></td>
          <td class="num">c. 1425</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>The forty-pillared mandapam</strong><br />
            <span style="color:var(--ink-soft); font-size:15px">Carvings of Krishna, Anjaneya, Garuda, Lakshmi and Vigneshwara with their vahanas</span></td>
          <td class="num">&middot;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Six musical pillars</strong><br />
            <span style="color:var(--ink-soft); font-size:15px">In the Kalyana Mandapam. Tapped gently, they sound the sapta swaras in correct arohana and avarohana</span></td>
          <td class="num">&middot;</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>On the accounts above.</strong> They are drawn from published sources, not
      from temple records, and the sources disagree with one another on dates. Treat them
      as the best public account rather than the authoritative one. Where the temple's own
      version differs, the temple is right.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .tower { margin: 22px 0 8px; text-align: center; }
  /* Centring lives on the classes, not on `.tower svg`. With Astro's scoping attribute
     that descendant selector scores higher than `.tower-anno`, and silently beat the
     display:none below, so both drawings rendered at once on a phone. */
  .tower-plain, .tower-anno { display: block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%; }
  .tower-plain { max-width: 132px; color: var(--ink); }
  .tower-anno { max-width: 430px; }

  /* On a phone the leader labels would set at about 8px, so the annotated drawing is
     dropped and the same dates are carried by the visible key instead. */
  .tower-key { text-align: left; margin-top: 14px; }
  .tower-key ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 7px; }
  .tower-key li { font-size: 14.5px; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .tower-key b {
    font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 12px; color: var(--kumkum);
    margin-right: 9px; font-weight: 600;
  }

  @media (min-width: 40rem) {
    .tower-plain { display: none; }
    /* clipped, not removed: the dates still reach a screen reader */
    .tower-key {
      position: absolute; width: 1px; height: 1px; margin: -1px; padding: 0;
      overflow: hidden; clip: rect(0 0 0 0); clip-path: inset(50%); white-space: nowrap;
    }
  }
  @media (max-width: 39.999rem) {
    .tower-anno { display: none; }
  }
</style>
